</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FC916554FFF6FFFCFF6945F5C2E3FF15" box="[199,957,153,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="B43436DFFFF6FFFCFF6945F5C2E3FF15" blockId="2.[151,1437,153,683]" box="[199,957,153,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">
<emphasis id="86FFEACDFFF6FFFCFF6945F5C010FF15" bold="true" box="[199,334,153,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">Etymology.</emphasis>
The family name is based on the 
<typeStatus id="6B30887DFFF6FFFCFD6645F5C3A6FF15" box="[712,760,153,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">type</typeStatus>
genus 
<emphasis id="86FFEACDFFF6FFFCFCE945F6C2E3FF15" box="[839,957,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFCE945F6C2E7FF15" authorityName="Alves &amp; Lowry &amp; Johnsson" authorityYear="2020" box="[839,953,154,179]" class="Malacostraca" family="Megaluropidae" genus="Magnovis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="575" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Magnovis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FC916554FFF6FFFCFF6945D1C294FD0D" pageId="2" pageNumber="575" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B43436DFFFF6FFFCFF6945D1C346FEB9" blockId="2.[151,1437,153,683]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">
<emphasis id="86FFEACDFFF6FFFCFF6945D1C065FF71" bold="true" box="[199,315,189,215]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">Remarks.</emphasis>
The 
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFED445D1C358FF71" box="[378,518,189,215]" family="Magnovidae" pageId="2" pageNumber="573" rank="family">Magnovidae</taxonomicName>
is distinct from all other hadziidan families in having, among other characters, antenna 1 shorter than the peduncle of antenna 2, a molar dominating the mandible and well-developed basofacial setae on the peduncle of uropod 1.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B43436DFFFF6FFFCFF694445C478FE09" blockId="2.[151,1437,153,683]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">
Buccal appendages are morphologically similar to calliopioidean amphipods, such as 
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFB274445C01AFEC1" authority="Barnard &amp; Karaman, 1987" authorityName="Barnard &amp; Karaman" authorityYear="1987" class="Malacostraca" family="Calliopiidae" genus="Membrilopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="575" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="86FFEACDFFF6FFFCFB274445C440FEE5" box="[1161,1310,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">Membrilopus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="D01A4B2EFFF6FFFCFA8B4445C01AFEC1" author="Barnard, J. L. &amp; Karaman, G. S." pageId="2" pageNumber="575" pagination="856 - 875" refId="ref4018" refString="Barnard, J. L. &amp; Karaman, G. S. (1987) Revisions in the classification of Gammaridean Amphipoda (Crustacea). III. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 100 (4), 856 - 875." type="journal article" year="1987">Barnard &amp; Karaman, 1987</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFED44421C3E7FEC1" authority="K. H. Barnard, 1930" authorityName="K. H. Barnard" authorityYear="1930" box="[378,697,333,359]" class="Malacostraca" family="Eusiridae" genus="Regalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="575" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="86FFEACDFFF6FFFCFED44421C08FFEC1" box="[378,465,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">Regalia</emphasis>
K.H. 
<bibRefCitation id="D01A4B2EFFF6FFFCFDB84421C3E7FEC1" author="Barnard, K. H." box="[534,697,333,359]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575" pagination="1 - 326" refId="ref4064" refString="Barnard, K. H. (1930) Amphipoda. Discovery Reports, 5, 1 - 326. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 27664" type="journal article" year="1930">Barnard, 1930</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Moreover, in the 
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFC2B4421C54FFEC1" box="[901,1041,333,359]" family="Magnovidae" pageId="2" pageNumber="573" rank="family">Magnovidae</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="86FFEACDFFF6FFFCFBB64420C5D8FEC1" bold="true" box="[1048,1158,332,359]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="9DCC57B6FFF6FFFCFBB64420C5D8FEC1" box="[1048,1158,332,359]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575" rank="family">fam. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
the rami of uropod 3 are subequal in length and longer than peduncle, an apomorphic character state of the family 
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFBD8441DC5BDFE2D" authorityName="Krapp-Schickel" authorityYear="2008" box="[1142,1251,369,395]" class="Malacostraca" family="Maeridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="575" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Maeridae</taxonomicName>
, but the shape of rami are strongly ovate, with many long marginal setae, a character state which dominates the 
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFB1744F9C47CFE09" authorityName="Lowry &amp; Myers" authorityYear="2013" box="[1209,1314,405,431]" class="Malacostraca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" infraOrder="Hadziida" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="infraOrder">Hadziida</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B43436DFFFF6FFFCFF6944D5C205FDBD" blockId="2.[151,1437,153,683]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">
Several characteristics such as: (1) pilose antenna 2 cone gland; (2) the presence of slender and long setae on appendages; (3) significant reduction of carpus and propodus in pereopods 3–7; (4) and strong sexual dimorphism are also powerful apomorphies distinguishing the 
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFD69476DC209FDBD" box="[711,855,513,539]" family="Magnovidae" pageId="2" pageNumber="573" rank="family">Magnovidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B43436DFFFF6FFFCFF694749C294FD0D" blockId="2.[151,1437,153,683]" pageId="2" pageNumber="575">
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFF694749C00DFD99" box="[199,339,549,575]" family="Magnovidae" pageId="2" pageNumber="573" rank="family">Magnovidae</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFE4D4749C3D6FD99" authorityName="Udekem d'Acoz" authorityYear="2010" box="[483,648,549,575]" class="Malacostraca" family="Cheirocratidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="575" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cheirocratidae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="738B4D5CFFF6FFFCFD134749C239FD99" authorityName="Thomas &amp; Barnard" authorityYear="1986" box="[701,871,549,575]" class="Malacostraca" family="Megaluropidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="575" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Megaluropidae</taxonomicName>
in that all three families share a very short antenna 1, shorter than the peduncle of antenna 2. But cheirocratids do not have basofacial robust setae on uropod 1. Magnovids do not have dorsal spines on the urosomites. In addition, megaluropids have a normal molar, maxilla 2 with an oblique setal row on the inner plate, and very long seventh pereopods.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
